<comment type="function">
<text evidence="1">Essential for cellulose biosynthesis. May play a role in subcellular localization of an active cellulose biosynthesis apparatus at the bacterial cell pole.</text>
</comment>
<comment type="subcellular location">
<subcellularLocation>
<location>Cytoplasm</location>
</subcellularLocation>
<text evidence="1">Localizes at the cell pole.</text>
</comment>
<comment type="domain">
<text evidence="1">The N-terminal putative ATP-binding domain is required for function. The C-terminal region contributes to both localization and function in cellulose synthesis.</text>
</comment>
<comment type="disruption phenotype">
<text evidence="1">Deletion abolishes cellulose production.</text>
</comment>
<comment type="miscellaneous">
<text>Cellulose production is abolished in E.coli K12.</text>
</comment>
<comment type="similarity">
<text>Belongs to the BcsQ family.</text>
</comment>
<comment type="caution">
<text>Could be the product of a pseudogene. The function of BcsQ was determined in a cellulose-producing E.coli strain 1094, which has an intact copy of the gene.</text>
</comment>
